In 2003, during my first visit to Tokyo, I got to meet NIGO in person and what I saw changed my life forever. NIGO blew me away with his taste and curation. Everything he bought was an investment, something that clearly fit in a defined collection.

Looking through these pieces, it's like walking down memory lane for me. So many of these items are from iconic moments in fashion and culture, it's a history lesson.

As an adult, I‚Äôve lived in a number of places, but as far as I‚Äôm concerned, I‚Äôve only ever had one real home. My home is my family. My home is Barack. 

But here‚Äôs the thing‚Äîour marriage has never been perfectly 50-50. One of us is always needing more or giving more. We have to be willing to listen to each other, honestly and without defensiveness. Only then, can we evolve together.

Over the years, a lot of young people have asked me about marriage. And my response usually goes something like this: You have to prepare yourself for long stretches of discord and discomfort. You have to learn how to make real compromises in the way you‚Äôve lived as an individual. Glamorizing a relationship while you‚Äôre dating will lead you straight to difficulty once you‚Äôre married. You can‚Äôt paper over problems when you‚Äôre living with someone day in and day out. 

So you‚Äôve got to ask yourself: What are you trying to get out of this relationship? Have you truly thought it through? Do you want a wedding or do you want a lifelong partnership? Those are two very different things. Together, you are answering the question: Who are we and who do we want to be?

Now I want to hear from you. What advice would you share about marriage or relationships? #TheLightWeCarry

27 years ago, this guy promised me a life full of adventure. I‚Äôd say he‚Äôs delivered. Here‚Äôs to our next chapter of becoming empty nesters and discovering what‚Äôs next‚Äîwhile still feeling the magic that brought us together all those years ago. Happy anniversary, Barack. üíï

Today is the day. After a disturbing era of chaos and division, we are entering the next chapter of American leadership with the inauguration of @JoeBiden and @KamalaHarris. Right now, I‚Äôm feeling more than just relief at putting the past four years behind us. I‚Äôm feeling genuinely hopeful for what‚Äôs to come.
 
Joe Biden and Kamala Harris are the kind of leaders our nation deserves‚Äîdecent, hardworking people who reflect the best of our values. Most of all, they‚Äôre guided by empathy, honesty, and a willingness to put the needs of our country before their own. They‚Äôre determined to make life better for all Americans, and I know they will bring us back the stability that has been sorely lacking through what has been a devastating pandemic. Not to mention, we‚Äôll have terrific examples of leadership in @DrBiden and @DouglasEmhoff, as our new First Lady and Second Gentleman.
 
It‚Äôs no secret that the work ahead will be challenging. And no one person, even a president, is capable of waving a magic wand and fixing the problems that persist in this country. But this past year I‚Äôve seen folks from all over America step up like never before, whether it was peacefully protesting against racial injustice, registering first-time voters, or simply making sure a neighbor could safely get their groceries. It feels like we might finally be getting some momentum. And with @JoeBiden and @KamalaHarris in the White House, we can once again start thinking about building the future we want for ourselves and our children.

Photo Credit: @chuckkennedydc

I‚Äôm beyond thrilled that my friend Joe Biden and our first Black and Indian-American woman Vice President, Kamala Harris, are headed to restore some dignity, competence, and heart at the White House. Our country sorely needs it.

Thank you to all of you who poured every ounce of your hope and determination into this democracy over these past four years, registering voters, getting them to the polls, keeping folks informed. More votes were cast in this election than ever before. It‚Äôs because of you.

And after we celebrate ‚Äî and we should all take a moment to exhale after everything we‚Äôve been through ‚Äî let‚Äôs remember that this is just a beginning. It‚Äôs a first step. Voting in one election isn‚Äôt a magic wand, and neither is winning one. Let‚Äôs remember that tens of millions of people voted for the status quo, even when it meant supporting lies, hate, chaos, and division. We‚Äôve got a lot of work to do to reach out to these folks in the years ahead and connect with them on what unites us.

But we‚Äôve also got to recognize that the path to progress will always be uphill. We‚Äôll always have to scrape and crawl up toward that mountaintop. And two years from now, four years from now, there will once again be no margin for error. We see now the reality that we can‚Äôt take even the tiniest part of our democracy for granted. Every single vote must count ‚Äî and every single one of us must vote. And as a country, we should be making it easier, not harder to cast a ballot.

So it‚Äôs up to us to stay engaged and informed, to keep speaking out and marching on. We‚Äôve got to vote in even greater numbers in the upcoming Senate runoffs in Georgia ‚Äî and every state and local election going forward. We‚Äôve got to promise each other that our focus in this election won‚Äôt be an anomaly, but the rule. That‚Äôs how we can not only feel this way right now, but in the months and years ahead. It‚Äôs the only way we‚Äôll build a nation worthy of our children. 

My warmest congratulations again to Joe and Jill, Kamala and Doug ‚Äî and each of you who stepped up when your country needed you.

This week, I‚Äôve been reflecting a lot on where I was four years ago. Hillary Clinton had just been dealt a tough loss by a far closer margin than the one we‚Äôve seen this year. I was hurt and disappointed‚Äîbut the votes had been counted and Donald Trump had won. The American people had spoken. And one of the great responsibilities of the presidency is to listen when they do. So my husband and I instructed our staffs to do what George and Laura Bush had done for us: run a respectful, seamless transition of power‚Äîone of the hallmarks of American democracy. We invited the folks from the president-elect‚Äôs team into our offices and prepared detailed memos for them, offering what we‚Äôd learned over the past eight years.

I have to be honest and say that none of this was easy for me. Donald Trump had spread racist lies about my husband that had put my family in danger. That wasn‚Äôt something I was ready to forgive. But I knew that, for the sake of our country, I had to find the strength and maturity to put my anger aside. So I welcomed Melania Trump into the White House and talked with her about my experience, answering every question she had‚Äîfrom the heightened scrutiny that comes with being First Lady to what it‚Äôs like to raise kids in the White House.

I knew in my heart it was the right thing to do‚Äîbecause our democracy is so much bigger than anybody‚Äôs ego. Our love of country requires us to respect the results of an election even when we don‚Äôt like them or wish it had gone differently‚Äîthe presidency doesn‚Äôt belong to any one individual or any one party. To pretend that it does, to play along with these groundless conspiracy theories‚Äîwhether for personal or political gain‚Äîis to put our country‚Äôs health and security in danger. This isn‚Äôt a game. So I want to urge all Americans, especially our nation‚Äôs leaders, regardless of party, to honor the electoral process and do your part to encourage a smooth transition of power, just as sitting presidents have done throughout our history.

Happy as a clam. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚Ä¢ 1 pound spaghetti ‚†Ä
‚Ä¢ 1 pound of clams (smaller the better)‚†Ä
‚Ä¢ handful of chopped parsley‚†Ä
‚Ä¢ 2 cloves of garlic roughly chopped ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
**serves 4 OR me and my wife‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Put your clams in a bowl of very salty water for 20 minutes to purge them of any dirt. Discard any that are open before cooking. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Put the pasta on to boil in salted water ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Place a large frying pan on a medium to high heat add a glug of extra virgin Olive oil.  throw in your garlic and cook for one minute until soft (move garlic around the pan to prevent it from burning)‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Add your clams to the frying pan and turn heat to high. Cook until all or nearly all are open. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Add your parsley ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Drain pasta reserving one cup of pasta water ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Add cooked pasta to the frying pan with half of the reserved pasta water and toss. (Add more water if it looks too dry)‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Add salt and a splash of extra virgin olive oil to taste.

üí•NEW EXHIBITIONüí• ArtScience Museum, @spacelogicgroup and @sl.experiences present Attack on Titan: The Exhibition. Opening 19 February 2022, step in a world where humanity‚Äôs existence is threatened by gigantic humanoids at the long-awaited Attack on Titan: The Exhibition. 

Organised by SPACElogic and presented at ArtScience Museum, Attack on Titan: The Exhibition‚Äôs first foray into Southeast Asia serves as a culmination of Hajime Isayama‚Äôs master storytelling and artistic vision over the past decade. Based on the best-selling Japanese manga series written and illustrated by Hajime Isayama, the exhibition will provide visitors with a sense of his intricate worldbuilding and vivid characters. 

Featuring over 180 artworks by Hajime Isayama ranging from the manga's earliest days to the present, the exhibition will also showcase new pieces that have not been displayed anywhere else in the world alongside drafts and sketches from his archives. Visitors and fans will soon be able to step into Hajime Isayama's sprawling dystopia, which will include an immersive animated battle sequence set in The Great Titan Theatre as well as displays of Titans, characters and objects from the manga. 

Attack on Titan: The Exhibition will run from 19 February to 3 July 2022. Tickets are available for purchase from 20 January. Find out more here in our #linkinbio.

This neonate male dolphin was rescued Wednesday, May 10 after being spotted alone and in distress near Anclote Key. He was transported to our rescue center in Orlando because of our extensive experience caring for young dolphins. Upon arrival, our veterinary team performed an exam and determined that he was hours to days old, making his rescue all the more critical for survival. We are happy to report he is swimming on his own and learning to take a bottle, but he is still considered to be in critical condition. This baby (and others like him) would not have a chance if not for the incredible rescue work and partnership of accredited zoological facilities and the Southeast Stranding Network who come together to do what is best for animals every day. We thank @epic_tails_charters who originally spotted him, @cmaquarium and @pascosheriffsoffice for transporting him to us for rehabilitation, and @noaafisheries for their leadership.

The SeaWorld Coral Rescue Center officially opens this afternoon! In partnership with @wildlife.florida, SeaWorld‚Äôs Coral Rescue Center aims to address the urgent need to protect and repopulate these corals, which are susceptible to the devastating Stony Coral Tissue Loss Disease. Come by the Coral Rescue Center during your next visit to observe and interact with biologists working to repopulate the Florida Reef Tract!

Our Rescue team recently received a Guadalupe fur seal pup from our partners at @cimwi. The young male was rescued after he was found stranded on a road, displaced after a storm. CIMWI provided the pup with immediate medical care and have moved him to SeaWorld San Diego, where we'll be caring for him long-term as he begins journey to recovery. The rescue team and veterinarians are providing around-the-clock care and monitoring the pup to ensure his health continues to improve.‚Äã

Guadalupe fur seals are recovering from near extinction and are listed as threatened under the Endangered Species Act and depleted under the Marine Mammal Protection Act. As a Marine Mammal Health & Stranding Response Program partner, SeaWorld has the expertise and @noaafisheries authorization for Guadalupe fur seal rehabilitation.

This weekend, four manatees (Lizzo, Cardi-Tee, MaryKate, and Ashley) made their way to our partners at @columbuszoo to continue their rehab journey thanks to the help of @dhl_global. Each of these juvenile manatees (three of them orphaned) came to us very under weight and because of this, they require long-term rehab before they can return to their natural environment. While it‚Äôs unclear whether they were struggling as part of the unique mortality event in Florida, these manatees will have a shot at a healthy life thanks to the rescue and veterinary teams that have cared for them over the last year, and the teams that will oversee this next part of their recovery.

SeaWorld has been at the forefront of marine animal research ever since the opening of the Hubbs-SeaWorld Research Institute back in 1963. In 2022 alone, our scientists have published 18 new studies that are critical to conservation efforts, as what we are able to learn from the animals in our care helps conserve wild populations of these species, some of which are vulnerable and endangered. On a recent episode of our Sea the World podcast, we sat down with VP of Conservation Research Dr. Robeck to learn more about the important work and what it means for the future of marine species across the globe. Germany is opening its doors wider to the world with a modernized citizenship law that allows dual citizenship! This step forward not only makes it easier for foreigners living and working in Germany to become citizens, but also paves the way for a diverse and vibrant community.

According to SDP member Daniela Behrens, ""Germany needs regulated migration to strengthen its economy."" And she's right! With its rich history, stunning landscapes, and thriving cities, Germany has long been a destination for travelers and professionals alike.

Imagine immersing yourself in the vibrant culture of Berlin, exploring the fairytale castles of Bavaria, or savoring the culinary delights of Munich. And now, with the new citizenship law, you can even consider calling this incredible country your home. While the law is set to be enforced from April 2024, it's important to remember that the application process for German citizenship can be lengthy.

Chris Mburu‚Äôs life was dramatically transformed by a stranger's small act of kindness when he was a child growing up in a small village in #Kenya.

His family couldn't afford his education. That was until Holocaust survivor Hilde Back, from #Sweden, offered to pay for him to go to school.

After attending Harvard and starting his first job as a human right lawyer at the #UnitedNations, Chris wanted to give back. Having found his long-lost childhood benefactor, Hilde, he set up a scholarship in her name to put Kenyan children through school.

‚ÄúWhen I look at poverty, it evokes memories of my own childhood. What keeps me going is the desire to keep as many people as possible out of poverty, because I remember my past, and where I was. I really do not want to see anybody there," he says.

In the new season of our podcast 'Awake At Night', Chris, who is now the UN Resident Coordinator in the Republic of Congo, reflects on his own path out of poverty, the transformational power of development and the ripple effect of compassion.

it deeply hurts me to be saying this, but after a lifelong battle with his inner demons, my lovely dad sadly decided to make the ultimate decision to take his own life last thursday. he peacefully passed away yesterday morning. my life will never be the same. 

my dad was a lot of things. he was a friend, a confidant, a cheerleader, an advisor, a philanthropist. his voice like a great big warm hug at the end of a long hard day. he listened intently to my every word, problem, achievement and always met each one with a smile. his wisdom, his stories and his way with words crafted my whole artistic identity. i couldn‚Äôt make the music i make without him. my dad was my best friend. 

he will be sorely missed by everyone especially my siblings and i. I can‚Äôt even tell you how sad i am, i‚Äôm wiping the tears away from my eyes as i write this, but the reason i have decided to post this is that this has just given me the most violent nudge to remind you all (especially men) to fucking talk to each other, man. speak about your feelings, reach out to one another and don‚Äôt hold back. be free with your deepest darkest thoughts, speak to people. let them know you‚Äôre in pain. we have the opportunity to save a generation and beyond thinking this way. 

lastly, to my lovely dad. i am so sorry i couldn‚Äôt have been your friend growing up. i‚Äôm sorry we couldn‚Äôt go for a walk or a pint and i couldn‚Äôt turn to you and really ask you if everything is okay. let you know it‚Äôs alright to chat to me. Tell you all the brilliant things that you are and will become. and just how much you meant to the people who knew you, but i will continue to share your story and let people know just how special you truly were. i will always miss you. whenever anyone asks me ‚Äúhow‚Äôd you get that wonderful beard?‚Äù, i always say ‚Äúi don‚Äôt know, ask my dad‚Äù‚Ä¶. well i guess we will never know now.

i love you, dad. may you rest in glorious peace.

some turn invisible, but that‚Äôs not original. might not be invincible, but you‚Äôre still my hero, dad.

When Taylor Swift released ‚ÄúSpeak Now (Taylor‚Äôs Version)‚Äù this month, there was no doubt it would debut at No. 1. The only questions were how forcefully it would smash records, how many mountains of vinyl it would sell and how far down the chart Swift‚Äôs catalog would push everybody else.

‚ÄúSpeak Now (Taylor‚Äôs Version),‚Äù the third installment in Swift‚Äôs series of rerecorded albums ‚Äî this one recreating ‚ÄúSpeak Now‚Äù from 2010, with a thick appendix of tracks revisited from the cutting-room floor ‚Äî is the year‚Äôs biggest new LP, notching the equivalent of 716,000 sales in the U.S. It easily topped Morgan Wallen‚Äôs ‚ÄúOne Thing at a Time,‚Äù which opened with 501,000 in March.

But that is not all. It is Swift‚Äôs 12th No. 1 album, beating Barbra Streisand for the most chart-toppers by a woman. Drake also has 12 No. 1 albums, but the only acts with more are Jay-Z (14) and the Beatles (19).

The popularity of Swift‚Äôs Eras Tour has lifted her entire catalog, and this week, in addition to the new ‚ÄúSpeak Now,‚Äù she has three other titles in the Top 10 of the Billboard 200 album chart: ‚ÄúMidnights‚Äù (No. 5), ‚ÄúLover‚Äù (No. 7) and ‚ÄúFolklore‚Äù (No. 10). Swift is the first living act to have four albums in the Top 10 since Herb Alpert in 1966. (Prince had five after his death in 2016, and for many years Billboard barred older ‚Äúcatalog‚Äù albums from reappearing on its main chart ‚Äî a rule that was changed after Michael Jackson‚Äôs death, in 2009.)

Why did 488 golden retrievers gather in Scotland?

Around 4 p.m. on July 13, 488 dogs assembled on the broad lawn in front of the ruins of Guisachan House in the Scottish Highlands to take a group photo of the 2023 Guisachan Gathering, a kind of golden retriever convention, commemorating the anniversary of the founding of the breed.

Since the first group photo was taken in 2001, golden lovers have come together about every five years to pay homage to Sir Dudley Marjoribanks, later Lord Tweedmouth, who lived in what was then Guisachan House. Sir Dudley is credited with developing the golden retriever in 1868, when he bred a wavy-coated retriever with a tweed water spaniel. He wanted a rugged hunting companion with a beautiful head, a loving disposition and soft, melting eyes, a dog that lived to fetch game. An obsession with tennis balls and rolling in filth apparently also came with the package.

People and their dogs travel from around the world to take part in the Guisachan Gathering, and this year‚Äôs was the biggest yet. Represented this year were Ireland, Bavaria, Switzerland, the Czech Republic, the U.S., Australia, Canada and Croatia.

Besides the photo, what else do the dogs get up to? Tap the link in our bio to read more from @nyttimestravel about the golden retrievers‚Äô gathering in Scotland. Photos by @invernessphotographer

The Supreme Court on Friday overruled Roe v. Wade, eliminating the constitutional right to abortion after almost 50 years in a decision that will transform American life, reshape the nation‚Äôs politics and lead to all but total bans on the procedure in about half of the states.

The ruling will test the legitimacy of the court and vindicate a decades-long Republican project of installing conservative justices prepared to reject the precedent, which had been repeatedly reaffirmed by earlier courts. It will also be one of the signal legacies of President Donald J. Trump, who vowed to name justices who would overrule Roe. All three of his appointees were in the majority in the 6-to-3 ruling.

The decision, which echoed a leaked draft opinion published by Politico in early May, will result in a starkly divided country in which abortion is severely restricted or forbidden in many red states but remains freely available in most blue ones.

Chief Justice John G. Roberts Jr. voted with the majority but said he would have taken ‚Äúa more measured course,‚Äù stopping short of overruling Roe outright. The court‚Äôs three liberal members dissented.

On Saturday, a gunman opened fire at a supermarket in Buffalo, killing 10 people and injuring three more, almost all of them Black, in one of the deadliest racist massacres in recent American history. 

The victims had been doing Saturday-afternoon shopping. They included a 65-year-old woman who was there to buy strawberries for shortcake and a 32-year-old woman who stopped by to pick up something for dinner. And there was the security guard, Aaron Salter Jr., 55, a retired Buffalo police officer.

During his 30 years as a police officer, Salter earned a reputation for bravery, with more than one of his exploits recorded in the local newspaper, The Buffalo News. He once chased down an arsonist, the newspaper reported, and on another occasion he faced down a burglar armed with a shotgun.

Salter retired in 2018, switching to a job that should have been far less treacherous: working as a security guard with the Tops supermarket in east Buffalo.

But on Saturday, Salter would once again encounter a situation that would test his bravery when a man ‚Äî wearing body armor and camouflage gear and armed with an assault weapon ‚Äî stormed into the supermarket and opened fire.

Salter confronted the gunman and fired back. But he became one of the 10 people, including three other store employees and several shoppers, who were killed. 

The names of the people fatally shot were released by the authorities on Sunday night. The people who were wounded included Christopher Braden, 55, of Lackawanna, New York; Zaire Goodman, 20, of Buffalo; and Jennifer Warrington, 50, of Tonawanda, New York.

Monica Poli, 57, who lives in Venice, has become prominent on social media for patrolling the streets of her hometown, calling out would-be pickpockets to tourists. She is part of a group known as the Cittadini Non Distratti ‚Äî the undistracted citizens ‚Äî that wanders the city shouting at people whom they believe to be thieves plucking wallets, passports and other items from the pockets of passers-by. Sometimes Poli and her fellow amateur watchdogs will report these suspected pickpockets to the police. In 2019, The Economist reported that the group was responsible for a third of all pickpocket arrests made in Venice.

The civilian group has been active for decades but only recently joined TikTok and Instagram, where hundreds of thousands of people follow along, thanks in large part to Poli‚Äôs unmistakable voice. Her shouts of ‚ÄúAttenzione, borseggiatrici! Attenzione, pickpocket!‚Äù have become a meme.

CEREMONY
The ceremony was something we‚Äôve been dreaming of for a long time. Along with the help of our wedding planners, we put in a lot of thought designing what exactly we wanted for this monumental moment and it came together even better than we had imagined. The ceremony location was at one of the highest points on the Epoch property which overlooks miles of wine country in Paso Robles. The colors surrounding us at this time of year are exactly why we love the Fall season so much. In an effort to provide shade and intimacy we installed a wooden truss system and semi sheer white draping, to create a relaxing and partially shaded ceremony location. White florals and lush greenery trailed up the columns of the wooden
structure and down the ceremony aisle. Beautiful white floral blooms surrounded us on a circle riser stage. As guests arrived by shuttle, they were invited to take a walk through the vineyard to the ceremony site. Our pastor and dear friend Judah Smith officiated the ceremony. It couldn‚Äôt have been more perfect. We exchanged hand written vows in front of the people we love most. Looking around and seeing the faces of each and every single person there, really put into perspective what is most important in life. Love. The sun set just as we said our ‚ÄúI Do‚Äôs‚Äù and the most beautiful pink sky was our backdrop as we walked back down the aisle as Mr. and Mrs. Taylor Lautner for the first time.

This is the deliberate bombing of a trapped population who have nowhere to flee. Gaza has been an open-air prison for nearly two decades and is fast becoming a mass grave. 40% of those killed are innocent children. Whole families are being murdered. While the world watches and with the active support of many governments, millions of Palestinian civilians - children, women, families - are being collectively punished and dehumanized, all while being deprived food, medicine and humanitarian aid against international law. This is a letter I was sent from a teenage girl in Afghanistan. Right now, the people of Afghanistan are losing their ability to communicate on social media and to express themselves freely. So I‚Äôve come on Instagram to share their stories and the voices of those across the globe who are fighting for their basic human rights.
 
--

I was on the border of Afghanistan two weeks before 9/11, where I met Afghan refugees who had fled the Taliban. This was twenty years ago.
 
It is sickening to watch Afghans being displaced yet again out of the fear and uncertainty that has gripped their country. 

To spend so much time and money, to have blood shed and lives lost only to come to this, is a failure almost impossible to understand.

Watching for decades how Afghan refugees - some of the most capable people in the world - are treated like a burden is also sickening. Knowing that if they had the tools and respect, how much they would do for themselves. And meeting so many women and girls who not only wanted an education, but fought for it.

Like others who are committed, I will not turn away. I will continue to look for ways to help. And I hope you‚Äôll join me.

I‚Äôm so inspired by young people around the world who are on the front lines of the struggle for human rights. From protecting the environment to fighting inequality and discrimination, they are stepping in to do the work adults should but so far have failed to do. And in refugee camps and conflict areas globally, children are bearing the burden of the consequences of those bad decisions. 

When children and young people have the agency, power and knowledge to speak up, they can change the lives of both young people and adults, helping to achieve a more equal society. 

That is the message of our new book, Know Your Rights and Claim them, which was written in consultation with young activists around the world - and is for them, and all the many young people fighting for their rights globally.¬†

I started working with displaced people because I believe passionately in human rights. Not out of charity, but out of a deep respect for them and their families, and all they continue to overcome, despite so much persecution, inequality and injustice.

Today, 1% of the world‚Äôs population - 82.4 million people - is displaced. That‚Äôs nearly twice as many as a decade before. 

Some crises, like the war in Afghanistan, have lasted for decades. 

Others, like the conflict in Ethiopia, are more recent.

They all have in common the violence and denial of rights that leave innocent families with no choice but to flee. 

At which point will we be concerned enough to address the environmental devastation, conflict and human rights abuses that fuel these crises? 

I‚Äôm always continuing to learn ‚Äì if you‚Äôd like to join me, please visit the UN @refugees account.

Started the year off in the cold mountains of Poland doing the most extreme thing we‚Äôve ever done. We arrived back in LA yesterday, and right now we‚Äôre on a flight headed to Tokyo to be a part of something truly legendary. We want you to be a part of it. We‚Äòre unable to mention the details but basically we‚Äôre bringing the Yes Fam around the world to participate in an art installation at one of the most respected museums in the world. How many people can say that they‚Äôve been a part of an art piece at a world class museum? Exactly!!! Not a lot.
What we want you to do is quite simple: Organize/ show up to a meet up in your city with yes fam members, stand in a circle holding hands then send us a video of it (the more creative the better -drone shots would be epic‚Äîthis will be a part of a Yes Theory episode)... After 6+ months of training, @mattdajer competed and finished his first ever Ironman this past weekend. That‚Äôs a 2.4-mile (3.86 km) swim, a 112-mile (180.25 km) bicycle ride, and a marathon 26.22-mile (42.20 km) run. Seems like pure insanity to most of us.

This is a photo from right after he finished. And it is the epitome of everything Yes Theory stands for. It‚Äôs pursuance of a dream despite whatever adversities, obstacles, fears, or limitations stand in your way. 
What you don‚Äôt see in this picture are the early morning runs, the 6+ hour solitary bike rides, the boring salads he ate, or the festivals he missed. You don‚Äôt see how a guy went from struggling through his first half-Ironman to crushing his second. And then again how that same guy showed up in Santa Rosa and completed a sub-12 hour race (un-freaking-believable). Today, let Matt be your inspiration. Start pursuing that goal that you think is way too far outside your reach. Sign up for a local triathlon. Write the first page of your book. Commit to an Improv class. Do something that your future self will thank you for. Just start.

Our collective potential is so much higher than we think it is. We can push our bodies and minds much further than we think we can. But, as Matt‚Äôs shown us, it takes an insane dedication to reach those heights‚Ä¶ 
PS - Video coming soon.

Dear Yes Fam,

As I step away from making videos, I can‚Äôt help but look back at how this dream all unfolded.

When the guys and I started out on this adventure in the summer of 2015, we had no idea what would happen. We were looking for an alternative path. We felt that life was too short to not take massive risks. And to be honest, we sometimes wondered if we were crazy. Our friends and our family thought we‚Äôd lost our minds. While everyone else we knew was getting jobs, we were packed into a one bedroom apartment dressing up as Superheroes and running around Montreal.

And soon, you came in. One by one. First in views, then in likes, then in comments and eventually, in person. We began to see that we weren‚Äôt the only ones who felt this way. That we weren‚Äôt the only ones who thought that life should be a daring adventure. That it shouldn‚Äôt be taken too seriously. That discomfort was something to be pursued, not avoided. Your belief in the Yes Theory philosophy is what made Yes Theory what it is today.

As I look back at what we‚Äôve accomplished in these five and a half years, the thing I am proudest of is you. There is no community like you online. The support you give each other is unheard of. The vulnerability you share with each other is unparalleled. Even when we‚Äôre not posting videos, you‚Äôre organizing events, launching ideas together, and even getting married. The Yes Fam is such a gift to this world. I hope you see it as much as I do. And I pray that you continue meeting up, dancing, and creating together. The world needs it more than ever. As for me, I‚Äôll still be here, you just won‚Äôt see my face as much. I‚Äôll be working hard behind the scenes to write this book that I wish I‚Äôd had when I was 19 and starting out on my life adventure. I‚Äôll also be writing a short newsletter twice a month which will help you transform into the person you want to become. The link to sign up to that is in the bio.

This is not the end. Far from it. It‚Äôs part of the evolution.

Thank you for your endless love. Thank you for your dedication to this movement. And thank you for being you. May the journey continue.

Love, Matt

Exactly a year ago today we were in Kyiv after finishing our mini-documentary about Chernobyl.

A few months before that we‚Äôd traveled to Afghanistan. 

It is needless to say that we have been watching the events in Ukraine and last summer in Afghanistan unfold with horror. Concerned for our friends we met and in disbelief that this is still happening in our lifetime.

To be honest, we‚Äôve been struggling with knowing how to best respond in both of these situations. As we‚Äôve tried to type captions and share our perspective, we feared to contribute to more noise on social media. So instead we decided to focus our internal efforts on what we could impact: to help the friends that we met on those trips reach safe areas.

It is heart-wrenching to see these conflicts arise around the world and seeing innocent people suffer. Yes Theory is a movement and community that will always stand for peace, empathy for each other and operates on the fundamental belief that we are a worldwide family.

As we also traveled to remote parts of Sakha Republic in Russia a month ago, we met some of the warmest people we‚Äôd ever encountered, it is clear that most of us simply want peace and to care for each other.

Aggression is never the answer, war is never the answer. Our hearts are with all of those impacted by this conflict.

#LoveOverFear

It‚Äôs happening.

September 25th, 2018.

@willsmith will be bungee jumping out of a helicopter with us on his 50th birthday.

Over the freaking Grand Canyon.

Live on @youtube .

And, a few days after it happens, something else will catch your attention. 
And you‚Äôll move on.

But here‚Äôs why we want you to remember this event, this picture and this story.

Here‚Äôs why it‚Äôs important for you.

Because the jump isn‚Äôt the significant part.

It‚Äôs what it represents.

For all of us.

It represents a choice.

One we all have to make.

A daily decision‚Ä¶

Love or fear.

Discomfort or comfort.

Speaking the truth or staying quiet.

See, Will is terrified of heights.

He‚Äôs gonna be 50.

He‚Äôs got a family he loves.

He‚Äôs got one of the most successful careers in the history of entertainment.

And yet, he‚Äôs agreed to a stunt that‚Äôs only been done a handful of times.

He‚Äôs got all of the excuses in the world.

He could easily have ignored our challenge.

But this, like so many other times in his life, is his choice to fight that voice inside his head.

That reminds him why he can‚Äôt.

That throws excuses at him.

That says he‚Äôs got too much to lose.

This is a f*** you to that voice.

It‚Äôs a choice.

And the choice is yours as well. 
We want this stunt to be a reminder for you to make that decision.

To take the leap while looking fear directly in the face.

As Will once said, ‚ÄúI'm motivated by fear. Fear of fear. I hate being scared to do something. And I think what developed in my early days was the attitude that I started attacking things that I was scared of.‚Äù Let‚Äôs do this.

PS - the video is up on YouTube

When I first heard about Xavier, he‚Äôd been given one week left to live. His liver cancer of five years had spread and there was nothing doctors could do. His wonderful cousin Estefany introduced us and when I met him, I didn‚Äôt know what to say. Cameras were on. I felt guilty for filming such an intimate and difficult experience. It was a lot. But he took it all in stride. He made me feel comfortable. He wanted to chat.

I learned that his dream was to start a YouTube channel. He said it‚Äôd be about his life, his love for cars, his love for Dragonball Z. He had so much love in him and all he wanted to do was share it with the world.

Yet as the months rolled on, the pain got worse. Every time I‚Äôd visit he was skinnier and had more difficulty moving. He‚Äôd go in and out of consciousness. But he soldiered on. He continued beating the odds, day after day.

The last time I went to see him before he passed away, it was different than usual. We opened up more. We spent two hours talking like old friends. And at one point, it got silent and we both started to cry. For 30 minutes it was water works. We knew this could be the last time. We held each other tight. Holding on, wishing the moment could last forever. That there would be no need to let go.

And writing this now, I miss him so much. I miss texting him at random hours of the day about my insignificant worries and being reminded by him every time about what matters. I miss his endearing laugh. I miss the way he was never afraid to tell the truth as he saw it.

In just three months he became not only my brother but my biggest inspiration. He won. He went past what anyone, any doctor, any expert, thought was possible. And I hope we all take a lesson from him. To love life so much that we set our own terms on it. To realize that each new day is a win. To hold each other tight and take it all in while we‚Äôre still here.

I know he‚Äôs up there cheering us on.

I know he's smiling.

Love you forever, Xavier Romero -Matt

What makes an image realistic, and why?

‚ÄúThe Steeple‚Äù out now off our new record ‚ÄòBack From The Dead‚Äù out May 6! 

We started writing for this album about 3 months B.C. (Before Covid). After lockdown hit, the songs we were writing, seemed unimportant now that we were facing an uncertain future. During this time, I fell into dark place and something of an identity crisis. After all, who am I without the touring, lives shows and this intangible magic that is my existence, my purpose?

This album is the story of how I carved myself out of that darkness. It is a journey of navigating my mental health, debauchery, survival, redemption, rediscovery of my power, and somehow still having faith in humanity. I‚Äôm so grateful for this amazing community that gathers under the power of music. I know that so many of you will see yourselves in these songs, and be reminded that none of us are alone. So, Burn every fear, every doubt like a funeral fire. Scream every anthem and follow your reckless desires. Take back the crown that hangs at the gate, ready your march‚Ä¶steady your aim, for the heart is a soldier that never loses its way. Raise Your Horns.
 
-Lzzy Hale

It is with tremendous sadness that my brothers and I announce that Kirk Douglas left us today at the age of 103. To the world he was a legend, an actor from the golden age of movies who lived well into his golden years, a humanitarian whose commitment to justice and the causes he believed in set a standard for all of us to aspire to.

But to me and my brothers Joel and Peter he was simply Dad, to Catherine, a wonderful father-in-law, to his grandchildren and great grandchild their loving grandfather, and to his wife Anne, a wonderful husband.

Kirk's life was well lived, and he leaves a legacy in film that will endure for generations to come, and a history as a renowned philanthropist who worked to aid the public and bring peace to the planet.

Let me end with the words I told him on his last birthday and which will always remain true. Dad- I love you so much and I am so proud to be your son. #KirkDouglas
